! [[Close vowel|Close]]
| {{IPA link|ɪ|i}}
| 
| {{IPA link|ʊ|u}}
|-
! [[Mid vowel|Mid]]
| {{IPA link|e̞|e}}
| {{IPA link|ʌ̝|ʌ}}
| {{IPA link|o̞|o}}
|-
! [[Open vowel|Open]]
| colspan=2 | {{IPA link|ɐ|a}}
| {{IPA link|ɒ|ɔ}}
|}

* {{IPA|/i, u/}} are phonetically near-close {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪ}}, {{IPA link|ʊ}}]}}.{{sfnp|Urua|2004|p=106}}
* {{IPA|/e, ʌ, o/}} are phonetically true-mid; {{IPA|/ʌ/}} is also strongly centralized: {{IPA|[{{IPA link|e̞}}, {{IPA link|ʌ̝|ʌ̝̈}}, {{IPA link|o̞}}]}}.{{sfnp|Urua|2004|p=106}}
* {{IPA|/a, ɔ/}} are phonetically near-open; {{IPA|/a/}} is central rather than front: {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɐ}}, {{IPA link|ɒ|ɔ̞}}]}}.{{sfnp|Urua|2004|p=106}}

Between consonants, {{IPA|/i, u, o/}} have allophones that are transcribed {{IPA|[ɪ, ʉ, ə]}}, respectively.{{sfnp|Urua|2004|p=106}} At least in case of {{IPA|[ɪ, ə]}}, the realization is probably somewhat different (e.g. close-mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|e}}, {{IPA link|ɘ}}]}}), because the default IPA values of the symbols {{IPA|[ɪ, ə]}} are very similar to the normal realizations of the Ibibio vowels {{IPA|/i, ʌ/}}. Similarly, {{IPA|[ʉ]}} may actually be near-close {{IPAblink|ʉ̞}}, rather than close {{IPAblink|ʉ}}.

In some dialects (e.g. Ibiono), {{IPA|/ɪ, ʉ, ə/}} occur as phonemes distinct from {{IPA|/i, u, o/}}.{{sfnp|Urua|2004|p=106}}

===Tones===
Ibibio has two tones: high and low. As in English language, a word can be used to mean two or more different things based on the tone ascribed to it.{{sfnp|Urua|2004|p=107}}

