{{Infobox language |name=Pashayi |states=[[Afghanistan]] |ethnicity=[[Pashayi people]] |speakers={{sigfig|404,400|2}} |date=2000–2011 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=[[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]] |fam3=[[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]] |fam4=[[Dardic languages|Dardic]] |lingua=59-AAA-a |lc1=aee|ld1=Northeastern |lc2=glh|ld2=Northwestern |lc3=psi|ld3=Southeastern |lc4=psh|ld4=Southwestern |glotto=pash1270 |glottorefname=Pashayi }}
'''Pashayi''' or '''Pashai''' is a group of languages spoken by the [[Pashai people]] in parts of [[Kapisa Province|Kapisa]], [[Laghman Province|Laghman]], [[Nuristan]], [[Kunar Province|Kunar]], and [[Nangarhar]] Provinces in Northeastern [[Afghanistan]]. It belongs to the [[Dardic languages|Dardic]] branch of the [[Indo-Aryan languages]].<ref>{{cite book|first=Colin P.|last=Masica|title=The Indo-Aryan Languages|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|year=1991|page=440}}</ref> Most speakers are bilingual in [[Pashto language|Pashto]] with a literacy rate of about 25%, with the Pashayi languages having no written form prior to 2003.<ref>{{cite paper|last=Yun|first=Ju-Hong|year=2003|title=Pashai Language Development Project: Promoting Pashai language, literacy and community development|conference= Conference on language development, language revitalization and multilingual education in minority communities in Asia. 6–8 November 2003. Bangkok, Thailand|url=http://palaso.org/ldc/parallel_papers/ju-hong_yun.pdf}}</ref> There are four mutually unintelligible varieties, with only about a 30% lexical similarity:<ref name="e18" />
* Northeastern: Aret, Chalas (Chilas), Kandak, [[Korangal Valley|Korangal]], Kurdar dialects * Northwestern: Alasai, Bolaghain, Gulbahar, Kohnadeh, Laurowan, Najil, Nangarach, Pachagan, Pandau, Parazhghan, Pashagar, Sanjan, Shamakot, Shutul, Uzbin, Wadau dialects * Southeastern: Damench, Laghmani, Sum, and Upper and Lower [[Darai Nur District|Darai Nur]] dialects * Southwestern: Ishpi, Isken, Tagau dialects
A grammar of the language was written as a doctoral dissertation in 2014.<ref>Lehr, Rachel. 2014. ''A descriptive grammar of Pashai: The language and speech of a community of Darrai Nur.'' Phd dissertation, University of Chicago.</ref>
