'''Yakoma''' are an ethnic group in the [[Central African Republic]] (CAR) who make up 4% of the population of the country.{{cn|date=January 2013}} 10,000 also reside in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]].<ref>Lewis, M.&nbsp;Paul (ed.). ''Ethnologue: Languages of the World'', 16th&nbsp;ed. "[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=yky  Yakoma. A language of Central African Republic]". SIL International ([[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]]), 2009. Online version.</ref>

They gave their name to the city of [[Yakoma, Democratic Republic of the Congo|Yakoma]] at the confluence of the [[Uele River|Welle]] and [[Mbobou River|Mbobou]] rivers and provided the land for the French post at [[les Abiras]] which served as the first capital of [[Ubangi-Shari]], the predecessor of the present-day CAR. The Yakoma are [[Bantu people|Bantu]] but speak a distinct dialect (also known as [[Yakoma language|Yakoma]]) similar to [[Sango]].<ref name="unhcr">Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada. "[http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/docid/3f7d4d6515.html Central African Republic: The Yakoma]." Accessed 9 Jan 2013.</ref>

[[André-Dieudonné Kolingba]], president of the CAR from 1979 to 1993, was a member of this group,<ref>United States Department of State. Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor. "[https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2001/af/8301.htm Country Reports on Human Rights Practices 2001]". 4 Mar 2002.</ref> as is the writer [[Adrienne Yabouza]].<ref name="journaldebangui.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.journaldebangui.com/article.php?aid=4979|title=JournalDeBangui.com: A lire: «La Maltraite des Veuves» dAdrienne Yabouza|publisher=|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref>
